Because **Ford trucks are not serving the same mission as Class 8 line-haul tractors**, so the business case for a **12-speed AMT** is much weaker.

Ford’s current strategy is very clear: **Super Duty uses Ford’s 10-speed TorqShift**, and Ford has said **every Super Duty** gets the Ford-designed 10-speed. Ford also says the current **F-650/F-750** use **Ford TorqShift transmissions** rather than a Class 8-style AMT path. ([https://www.ford.com/][1])

The core reason is this:

**A 12-speed AMT solves a Class 8 problem, not really a Super Duty problem.**

A heavy line-haul semi spends its life:

* grossing very high combined weights,
* cruising at highway speed for long hours,
* chasing every fraction of fuel economy,
* and benefiting from many closely managed ratios.

That is exactly where AMTs shine. They preserve the efficiency of a manual-style driveline and give the fleet lots of ratio control.

A Ford Super Duty or medium-duty Ford truck is usually doing something different:

* pickup towing,
* mixed unloaded/loaded driving,
* stop-and-go work,
* snowplow/upfit/PTO work,
* consumer and commercial use with refinement expectations,
* and much wider variation in duty cycle.

For that kind of product, a **10-speed full automatic** is a very strong compromise:

* smooth launch behavior,
* good towing feel,
* no torque interruption during shifts,
* simpler customer experience,
* and enough ratio spread for the mission.

Ford’s own messaging on Super Duty supports that logic: it emphasizes low-end torque for launch, towing capability, selectable drive modes, and PTO/upfit integration around the 10-speed TorqShift rather than ultra-dense highway ratio management. ([https://www.ford.com/][1])

There is also a **product-planning / cost** angle:

A 12-speed AMT would likely be worse for Ford’s core pickup customer in several ways:

* more shift events,
* more noticeable torque interruptions than a hydraulic automatic,
* less refined feel in daily driving,
* more calibration complexity across unloaded, trailer-tow, off-road, snowplow, and consumer use,
* and questionable payoff versus a 10-speed automatic that already covers the ratio spread Ford needs.

Also, Ford’s current 10-speed already has a deep first gear and multiple overdrives, so they are already getting much of the launch-plus-cruise benefit without moving to a Class 8-style AMT architecture. Third-party technical coverage of the 10R140 cites a **4.61:1 first gear** and **0.63:1 tenth gear**, illustrating that the transmission already spans a wide range. ([Gears Magazine][2])

So the clean answer is:

**Ford doesn’t use 12-speed AMTs in its trucks because Ford pickups and medium-duty trucks are not primarily long-haul semi tractors.** The customer priorities are smoother drivability, towing feel, versatility, PTO/upfit compatibility, and broad usability. For that, Ford has decided a **10-speed automatic** is the better fit than a **12-speed AMT**. ([Ford Media][3])

And the deeper punchline is:

**The market absolutely likes lots of gears — but the “right” architecture depends on the vehicle class.**

* **Class 8 tractor:** lots of gears via **AMT**
* **Ford pickup / medium duty:** lots of gears via **planetary automatic**

That is why a **12-speed AMT** makes sense in a highway semi, while a **10-speed full automatic** makes more sense in a Super Duty.

I can also lay out the engineering trade in a more transmission-nerd way: **10-speed planetary automatic vs 12-speed AMT**, point by point.

